segments.text: It meant that he didn't talk very much with students.
Yeah, that's why.
But all the students liked him.
Ha ha!
And he'd come in the classroom, he wouldn't have much to say.
But it was always something that was catching to the students and
they knew it was coming and they would wait till it came and then they'd get busy.
So then he demanded hard work and the students did it.
And the students did it.
He never had any trouble with the students at all as far as I know.
How about
Marsteller.
Well, Marsteller was a graduate from Ohio State too.
Most of the men were graduates from the northern schools and came south.
But C-3, Blackburn, he was from New York.
And he got his training in the school in New York.
Cornell?
No.
Yeah, Cornell.
And then there was Wright.
Yeah, Lewis Wright.
Lewis Wright.
And Wright, I forget now what school he was from.
And then there was...
Oh, oh heck.
Who was the other one?
Leonard, Leonard, Leonard Schmitt.
Schmitt, there was Hilbert Schmitt.
Oh, Schmitt, yeah.
Schmitt, he taught, he taught pathology in school, but he was glad to remain him himself.
And he was working for the Extension Service.
Yeah.
And Ralph Dunn.
Dunn was working for, he was an Ohio State man too, but he worked for down at the, what we call a clink, and he worked for the
the board of the college that had to do with Benedict Mason.
And he was considered a man of the faculty, but he mixed with the boys
used to sing.
Was he a good teacher, Dunn?
Well, he didn't teach very much.
He was mostly an outside man.
How about Blackburg?
Was he a good teacher?
Well, Blackburg, yeah, he was a good teacher, all right.
But his diction was

rather funny and uh being from new york being from new york well it took a good while to get a season in until the boys that that had to be seasoned and so by the way he's he's he he's a doctor in new york in new york
Oh really?
He went back to New York?
He went back to New York and took medicine.
And he, I don't know whether he's living or whether he's, what he's doing.
But once people got to under, became, or could understand him, then did you like him?
Did the students like him?
Oh yeah, they liked him all right.
He was very good to the students.
I don't think the vet department had any trouble at all while he was out there.
And Schmitt.
Who?
Schmitt.
What did you think of him?
Well, Schmitt was a graduate from A&M and worked for the same place that
See at A&M with the, I can't think of it now.
The headquarters used to be in the old, it's out there now, but the building was, when it was vacated, they took it over.
and they had all the officers, the male and female, of course they have both of them now, and they had ten because it was first being formed that A&M and then it went from there over the state.
Let me see what, oh heck.
Was he a good teacher?
Oh yeah, yeah.
He was a very good teacher.
He taught pathology.
And what about Lewis Wright?
Wright?
I thought we'd taken up Wright before.
He was a very good teacher and he taught
But I thought we had taken him up.
Okay, okay.
There was another one, too.
Yeah.
A guy by the name of Bailey Bethel.
Who?
Bailey Bethel.
B-E-T-H-E-L, Bethel.
He was teaching there at the time.
You probably didn't have him, then, did you?
No, I didn't have him.
Okay.
No, he was there the four years I was there.
And Lenard, August Lenard.
Lenard, August Lenard.
He was the...
He got his veterinary medicine at, I believe he went to school at, I believe at Kansas City.
And then when he graduated and everything, well he came down there and started to work
the vet department at A&M.
And he taught vet medicine.
I mean, sure he taught vet medicine, but I mean, he taught obstetrics, whatever, he taught obstetrics.
But he did.
Now what, when you went out in the field as a veterinarian for four years, did you feel
Looking back, did you feel that A&M at the college or school of vet medicine then had given you a good education?
Did they prepare you?
Yeah, they prepared me about as good as it could be done.
Plenty of clinical work.
Men all over the state were sending animals to A&M.
Because that's the only place they had to send them.
And they put them in a, either they came in a car or they came in a trailer, hitched to a hitched to a car and came to College Station with a horse.
So there was an emphasis on clinical work down then.
You got a lot of experience before.
Yeah, it was a lot of work on clinical work.
I got a lot of experience.
Before you even graduated, right in school you got plenty of experience.
Oh yeah.
Did you know when you were out in the field working for the state, did you know other veterinarians?
Oh yes.
And who were not graduates of A&M?
I met quite a few of them.
And could you compare, did you think that your schooling at A&M was better than theirs or could you make some comparisons, do you remember?
Well, we didn't have much to do with the fellows that wasn't graduates.
from a recognized school.
We didn't have very much to do with them.
And they didn't, they didn't phone in and have someone come out to help them.
As far as I know.
Did your vet school, did the fact that you were a veterinarian and then a practicing veterinarian for four years, did that help you in medical school?
Well, see I took a veterinary medicine to help me a whole lot in medical school.
Now let's talk for a minute about that famous football team that you were on.
Could you tell me the positions that you played on the football team here at A&M?
Well, I was a quarter and a half back.

and playing and we were either started the game or we went in later on and relieved the men that were either hurt or they were tired and needed some further rest and we would have to go in and run the team just the same as
as they were there.
There wasn't any jealousy.
In other words, there was good spirit among the team members?
There was good spirit among the team members.
No man was better than anybody else.
They were all the same.
when that whistle blew to start the game, we was ready to go.
And when we were out practicing during the weekend, during the week, well we was always there on time.
Bob was our coach then.
And he was the coach of A&M for seven or eight years before he went to
Oh, he went north.
In 17 he had to go and straighten the team out and he fought half the men that was on the team and put the second class men because the others, they didn't want to put out any.
And so when Bob, the first two or three weeks when he was there, well, he got a leave of absence from A&M.
And that was a 17 team, too.
Yeah, yeah.
That was some team that you were on.
Yeah, I was on the same team, 17 and 19.
Yeah, mm-hmm.
And that was the year that
the A&M team had that remarkable record of nine wins and no losses.
Yeah, well we had the same thing again in 19.
Had nine wins and no losses.
And one year we scored 275 points and didn't allow the opponents to score one point.
That's right.
That was absolutely fantastic.
Now how can, why do you think, what was, why were we so good?
Well,
We were, just like I said before, there wasn't any jealousy amongst the boys, and they all prayed to win.
And we did win.
And we were clean about it.
Wasn't any men on it that would hurt anybody.
And so they...
They just won.
We didn't kick a field goal.
I could drop kick 40 yards.
Yeah, I know.
You kicked a field goal against SMU.
Yes, right.
The 40-yard one.
Yes, right.
They held in that victory.
Yeah.
It was 12, 16-0, I believe it was.
Yes, it was, 16-0.
And so we didn't...
In fact, Ben's Bible didn't like to kick.
He said, score first and hold the score.
Well, they would get down pretty good, 10, 5 yards, but you couldn't go any further.
And they didn't have sense enough to kick the ball and get three points.
Well, the three points helped.
But they didn't do it, so they...
They beat themselves.
Yeah, right.
Do you remember the equipment that you used to have back in those days?
Well, it was very light stuff.
Yeah.
Very light.
And everybody that could bought their own.
Oh, really?
Oh, yeah.
The school didn't supply the equipment then?
They had equipment, but if you could buy your own equipment and meet that inspection, well, we could use it.
Sure.
And many of us boys used our own equipment, but they were light.
They were good stuff, but they were light.
Do you think that they were too light?
I mean, do you think that they didn't protect against injury?
Well, we didn't have very many hurt then.
Oh, good.
Very few knees.
We didn't have any knees and we didn't have any ankles.
Good.
Great.
I was thinking about that the other day.
Now you have a good many of them.
Ankles are getting very prominent now.
Yes, they certainly are.
You never heard of an ankle fellow being hurt with a bad ankle, a broken bone ankle, anything like that.
How do you think that is?
Well, I think the reason why the...
You see, a bone that's just fractured very lightly, and it hurts at the time that it happened.
But by a week, it's in pretty good shape.
And no man, as far as I know, no one played.
except those that wanted to.
And if they were good enough to play, well, they played.
If they wanted regular team.
So that's the way it was.
I wanted to ask another question.
Sure, go right ahead, ask all you want.
Okay, I wanted to...
ask if World War I had any impact on A&M because you were, this is the same time when you're in college that the United States is fighting in World War I.
Did that war seem to have any impact on the college?
Do you remember?
Oh, it didn't have, it didn't have very much.
It didn't have very much.
Did you ever think about going into the Army?
I was in the Army.
And when was that?
I was in the Army in World War I and World War II.
And, see, the first war didn't last for about 18 months.
Yeah, right.
And the second war lasted four and a half years.
Yeah.
Another five years.
And so when did you go in for World War I?
Well, when I was, let's see, I went in there during the early part of 17.
Early part of 17.
And as soon as I was released, well, I went on out.
Well, see, I was at A&M all the time.
Yeah, I don't understand.
What you don't understand about it?
Well, if you were at A&M all the time and you were in the Corps, you were also in the regular Army at the same time.
Well, see, in the first war, I wasn't 18 years old until
If I remember correctly, I was about mid-season.
So I played the whole year.
Before I was 18 and after I got in the Army, they had to call me.
They had to draw my number and my number was tall.
Oh, I see.
See, they drew the numbers.
put all the stuff in a hat and capsule and shake it up and then they'd reach in there and get one.
But they never did get my number.
So I never was called.
So you registered for the draft then, but you never were called to serve in World War I?
No, I was, let me see.
No, I was in the Army, but I wasn't called up to work for them.
Right, right.
Okay.
Okay, I was also wondering about, there's been a lot of changes in the vet school since
You went there.
The only change that's been made that I know of is the new men that they hired out there, when they came to A&M, I think they were hired
A good many of them were graduates from the school.
And then when all the girls got in there, 125 or 135, I forget how many, when the school opened for them to sign up for the classes, well, they had 125 girls.
They wanted to come to A&M because the boys were there.
Yeah.
And so they had a big class.
Were you in favor of allowing women?
No, I wasn't in favor of that.
Why not?
Well, I just, I don't know.
I just wasn't in favor.
Mm-hmm.
But when they hadn't had it in the house, I took it as it was.
Now as a final question, I'd like to just ask your overall opinion of A&M.
If I had to do it over again, I'd go right there.
That's the best way I could put it.
If I had to do it over again, I'd go.
And I'd take the same subjects as I did before and stay with it until I graduated.
Now, we had one man that I haven't called a name yet that taught out there.
Well, we've talked about Mark Francis and Marsteller and Dunn, Bethel, and Leonard, Wright, Blackburg, and Schmitt.
And those are the people that I had on my list.
Now there might have been one or two more that I missed of people who taught out there during your...
I don't know.
Bethel, what Bethel was that?
Bailey Bethel.
And we don't, and I'll have to go back and check in my books.
on him, but I think he was listed as a teacher.
He must have been listed as a teacher.
And who else was it?
Dunn, Ralph Dunn.
Well, Dunn was... We talked about him.
Perry Marsteller.
Yeah, he was all right.
And Francis Leonard.
Yeah.
And we talked about Louis Wright.
Yeah, Wright.
He was a full-time man then, too.
Mm-hmm.
And Blackburg, we talked about him from New York, and Schmitt.
And Schmitt.
Mm-hmm.
Well, he didn't leave there.
He graduated there in, what did he graduate in?
He took vet medicine and he was from a town over there close to,
Well anyhow, he's in Texas and he's over that way.
I can't tell you where he's from.
Now, right now, I don't know exactly where he's from, but he was a very good man and he taught pathology.
And so I don't...
I don't remember anything else about the fellows that taught me.
There was one other fellow there, tall, slender, black, dark, and he went in the Army and landed over at
He landed at the post.
What was his name?
Oh, heck.
I can't call his name, say my name now.
But he was a good man.
He was a good man.
I can't call his name, but he was a good man.
You didn't mention him in that list that you had.
Well, I'll have to go back to my office and check then.
I might have missed somebody.
Let's see if I got this light.
Well, I'm out of questions now.
I think we've answered questions about the football team and about your opinion about A&M and about the vet school and your classmates and your teachers.
Well, you know, the vet school, they moved.
They already moved.
Yeah, I know they did, yeah.
across the railroad track.
Now they're going to have a medical school there.
Yeah, I know.
I see them building.
They're putting up a four-story building there.
What's your opinion of that?
Well, I think it's very good.
You think it's about time?
Yeah.
Because there's a good many of the subjects that they teach that can be...
the boys that are taking medicine can take and get credit.
Especially physiology, pharmacology, bacteriology, histology.
Those four things right there
They can, it's in a war.
What were your favorite classes when you were in vet school?
What subjects did you like the most?
Oh, like the most?
Well, I liked them all.
I don't know whether you like,
We liked one another.
You basically liked them all.
I liked them all.
Good.
I don't believe, but while I was at A&M, I didn't flunk a subject.
four years and I didn't flunk subjects.
And then when I got four years and I was married and when I went to medical school and the professors there, they knew more about me than I knew about myself.
I couldn't tell them anything, they knew it all.
And so,
You thought it was a great experience then for you.
Sir?
You thought it was a good experience, a great experience for you.
Oh yeah, yeah, yeah.
And it was hard for me to, it took me six months, about six months to get used to going to school again.
Because I was accustomed of being associated with the law.
